  "response_text": "When you have a cold, it's important to focus on foods and drinks that support your immune system, keep you hydrated, and soothe symptoms like sore throat or congestion. Here are some gentle, effective options:\n\n### 1. **Hydrating Liquids**\n   - **Warm water with lemon and honey**: Soothes sore throat, provides vitamin C, and honey can calm coughs.\n   - **Herbal teas**: Chamomile, ginger, peppermint, or elderberry (ginger helps nausea, peppermint clears sinuses).\n   - **Broth-based soups (especially chicken soup)**: Provides fluids, electrolytes, and may reduce inflammation.\n\n### 2. **Easy-to-Digest Foods**\n   - **Oatmeal or porridge**: Warm, soothing, and can be topped with honey or mashed banana for energy.\n   - **Plain rice or congee (rice porridge)**: Easy on the stomach, especially if you have nausea.\n   - **Scrambled eggs or tofu**: Soft, protein-rich foods that are gentle to swallow.\n\n### 3. **Nutrient-Dense Options**\n   - **Citrus fruits (oranges, grapefruit, kiwi)**: Vitamin C helps immune function.\n   - **Garlic and ginger**: Both have antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties. Add to soups or tea.\n   - **Yogurt with live cultures (probiotics)**: Supports gut health, which is linked to immunity.\n\n### 4. **Soothing Snacks**\n   - **Bananas**: Easy to eat, rich in potassium (especially if you’ve been sweating).\n   - **Applesauce**: Soft, hydrating, and provides vitamins.\n   - **Crackers or toast**: If you feel nauseous, these can settle your stomach.\n\n### 5. **What to Avoid**\n   - **Dairy (milk, cheese, ice cream)**: May thicken mucus for some people (though not for everyone).\n   - **Spicy or acidic foods**: Can irritate a sore throat.\n   - **Sugary drinks and processed snacks**: They can suppress immune function.\n   - **Alcohol and caffeine**: Dehydrate the body and interfere with rest.\n\n### **Key Tips**\n- **Stay hydrated**: Water, herbal tea, and broth are crucial.\n- **Listen to your body**: If you have no appetite, focus on liquids and light soups.\n- **Rest**: Your body needs energy to fight the virus, so prioritize sleep.\n\nIf symptoms persist or worsen, consult a healthcare professional. Otherwise, these simple, nourishing choices can help you recover more comfortably.",
